[3] Philippines (Manila)
Date: Wed, 10 Aug 2005 05:32:09 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Manila Standard Today, Phillipines, 9 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.manilastandardonline.com/?page=news06_aug10_2005>

16 new deaths from dengue
-------------------------
The Department of Health reports 16 new deaths from dengue and 1000
more new infections nationwide as cases continue to surge.
According to the latest Dept. of Health (DoH)-National Epidemiological Center
(NEC) dengue report, in a span of just 5 days, from 29 Jul to 3 Aug, the
number of deaths in 2005 has already risen to 159 from 143 and cases went up
from 10 977 to 12 308.
The total number of cases in 2005 is 15 percent higher compared to
the same period last year [2004] which saw 10 690 cases, DoH notes.
Epidemics and outbreaks where recorded by the DoH-NEC in 2 provinces:
Zamboanga City and Nueva Ecija. The outbreak in Zamboanga is now
under control, while cases in Gen. Tinio, Nueva Ecija continue to
increase and now stand at 99 cases with 2 deaths.
DoH-NEC recorded no current hot spots but noted clustering of cases (3 or more
cases in a span of 2 weeks) in barangays [districts] in Bukidnon (Poblacion,
Manolo Fortich; Kalunsugay, Malaybalay; Poblacion, Lantapan), Camiguin (Agoho
Mambajao; Bonbon, Catarman), and Misamis Oriental (Poblacion, Libertad;
Poblacion, El Salvador; Poblacion, Claveria).
Clustering of cases was observed in 13 barangays in Cagayan de Oro
city as well as in Quezon province. Other areas that have clustering
are Nueva Ecija, Bulacan, Malabon City and Manila (F. Varona Street
and Parola in Tondo; Anonas Street, Sta. Mesa; and Baseco Compound in
Port Area).
Barangay Pag-asa in Quezon City, which reported initially having 42
suspected dengue cases, has been confirmed to have only 2 cases from
24 to 30 Jul 2005.
Meanwhile, DoH advised parents to protect their kids who go to school
against dengue, as records show they are the ones prone to be bitten
by the day-biting _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.
NEC records reveal that most of the victims of dengue are children (43
percent) and many of them go to school. [Most adults are already immune to the
dengue types circulating in the country. - Mod.JW].
"The dengue-carrying mosquito, called _Aedes aegypti_, only attacks
during daytime, the time when our kids are out of our homes and in
schools," said Dr. Vito Roque, head of the surveillance unit of the
DoH National Epidemiological Center.
Last month [July 2005], an elementary school in Pangasinan panicked
after 6 of its students were diagnosed to be suffering from dengue.
Roque said parents can protect their kids from being bitten by
mosquitoes by applying mosquito repellant to their skin.
DoH also reminded school officials to engage in clean-up activities
at least once a week and pay attention to the removal of possible
breeding grounds of mosquitoes such as cans, bottles, used tires, and
clogged gutters that can accumulate water.
Water in flower vases should be replaced every 7 days and all water
containers should be covered tightly.
_Aedes aegypti_ lays eggs in standing water. The adult mosquitoes
seek dark places.
[Byline: Jherry L. Barrinuevo]
