[4] Philippines (Negros Occidental)
Date: Tue, 9 Aug 2005 06:10:09 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Sun Star, Phillipines, Tuesday, August 09, 2005 [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/bac/2005/08/09/news/dengue.cases.in.negros.oc
cidental.now.574.html>

Dengue cases in Negros Occidental now 574
-----------------------------------------
Negros Occidental has now had 574 dengue cases from January to July 2005.
Based on their records, Dr. Luisa Efren, provincial health officer,
said there has been a 40 percent increase in the number of cases
compared to the same period in 2004, which had total of only 373
cases.
There were also 2 deaths recorded in the latest PHO provincial health office)
monitoring. This is the reason why Efren had already raised the alert status
in the entire province on dengue. But she clarified that there is [not yet an]
epidemic and there is [no reason for public panic].
Efren, therefore, asked all Negrenses to be aware about the common
symptoms of dengue, which include high fever and flu, itchiness on
the stomach, nausea and vomiting.
She also enjoined all Negrenses to observe and be advocates of the 4
o'clock habit, a daily [regimen] that [includes] the burning of
garbage at 4 p.m. to produce smoke that will drive away
dengue-carrier mosquito -- "_Aedes aegypti_."
[Daily elimination] of breeding places -- especially flowerpots, mini
fishponds, among other bodies of stagnant water -- is also suggested.
Meanwhile, Dr. Jovy Vergara, assistant health officer of Bacolod, asked
Bacolenos not to kill or gather spiders for derby purposes. Vergara stressed
that spiders are predators that could deter the spread of dengue-carrying
mosquitoes. He said spiders usually trap mosquitoes in their webs for food.
--
