[5] Philippines
Date: Sun, 7 Aug 2005 08:22:09 -0400 (EDT)
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Khaleej Times, 7 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle.asp?
xfile=data/theworld/2005/August/theworld_August206.xml§ion=theworld&col=>

Philippine public urged to help fight dengue, which has killed 143
------------------------------------------------------------------
The Philippine government on Sunday urged the public to work with
health authorities in efforts to prevent an outbreak of dengue, which
has already killed 143 people in the country since the start of 2005.
Presidential spokesman Ignacio Bunye said President Gloria Macapagal
Arroyo has directed the Department of Health (DOH) to coordinate with
local government in affected areas.
"The president is satisfied with the anti-dengue measures being
implemented by the DOH," he said. "We also urge the public to help
our health authorities. Let us keep our surroundings clean,
especially areas where mosquitoes can breed."
According to the DOH, a total of 10 977 cases of dengue have been
recorded throughout the country from January to July, up 9 per cent
from 10 117 cases in the same period last year [2004].
During the 7-month period, 143 people have died [a CFR of 1303 per
100 000], mostly children, the DOH added. But it did not release
comparative figures for the deaths during the same period of 2004.
Dengue is a mosquito-borne disease that is endemic to the
Philippines. Its symptoms are high fever that could last 2-10 days
and headache, accompanied by loss of appetite, vomiting, red skin
rashes and abdominal pain.
