[6] Brazil
Date: 10 Aug 2005
From: Luz Alba Fornells <luzalba@bioqmed.ufrj.br>
Via: LISAS
Source: Correio Brasiliense Online 10 Aug 2005 11:30
[in Portuguese, summarized by Mod.JW, edited]
<http://noticias.correioweb.com.br/materias.php?id=2647263&sub=Brasil>

Dengue increases in 19 Brazilian states
---------------------------------------
The Secretary of Health Surveillance reports that after 2 years of decreasing
incidence, the number of dengue cases is increasing. From January through May
2005, 79 674 cases have been notified, 30 percent more than for the same
period last year (2004). There have been 72 cases of DHF and 5 deaths.
The greatest increase has been in the South, with an increase of 184 percent,
due mainly to Parana state, with 692 cases, followed by the North, with a 73
percent increase (26 934 cases). In the Northeast & West-Central regions the
increases were 51 percent, whereas the Southeast had a decrease of 27 percent,
with the states of Rio de Janeiro & Minas Gerais having the greatest decreases
of 35 percent � although they also had 10 cases of DHF (6 in Rio de Janeiro).
What is preoccupying about the increase is that this is occurring before the
traditional dengue season, which is during the rains in November, December &
January. Also, dengue type 4 has not been seen in Brazil since the 1980�s,
but is currently circulating in Venezuela, French Guiana, Colombia & Peru, all
neighboring countries to Brazil.
--
Luz Alba Fornells, PhD
Nucleus for Investigating Emerging Infectious Diseases - NIDIE
Institue of Medical Biochemistry
Center for Health Sciences
Fedral University of Rio de Janeiro - UFRJ
Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil
